  "text": "The Java source files that produce audit log entries for authorization decisions in Apache Kafka are located in the metadata module:\n\n1. **StandardAuthorizerData.java** (metadata/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/metadata/authorizer/StandardAuthorizerData.java): This class contains the core audit logging functionality for authorization decisions. It implements the `logAuditMessage()` method (line 281) which logs both ALLOWED and DENIED authorization events. The audit messages are constructed using the `buildAuditMessage()` method (line 254) which includes details about the principal, operation, resource, host, and the authorization decision (\"Allowed\" or \"Denied\"). The class uses a logger named \"kafka.authorizer.logger\" (line 116) configured via `LoggerFactory.getLogger(\"kafka.authorizer.logger\")` to write audit trail entries.\n\n2. **StandardAuthorizer.java** (metadata/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/metadata/authorizer/StandardAuthorizer.java): This is the built-in Kafka authorizer implementation that implements the ClusterMetadataAuthorizer interface. It uses StandardAuthorizerData internally to perform authorization checks and produce audit logs. The `authorize()` method (line 145) delegates to StandardAuthorizerData which triggers the audit logging.\n\nThe audit logging mechanism works as follows:\n- For ALLOWED results: When `action.logIfAllowed()` is true, the decision is logged at DEBUG level; otherwise at TRACE level (lines 292-296)\n- For DENIED results: When `action.logIfDenied()` is true, the decision is logged at INFO level; otherwise at TRACE level (lines 304-308)\n\nThese files implement audit trail functionality for ACL-based authorization decisions in Kafka's KRaft mode. The audit logs are essential for compliance and security auditing, tracking which principals are allowed or denied access to Kafka resources."
}

